body:
Tested on: 4.107 devel rev v4.106-54-gb15dd3f8 (master branch: commit b15dd3f)

As per the LRM each generate-construct (both named and unnamed) in a given scope is assigned a number. The generated names are assigned to the unnamed blocks _as per this assigned number_.

In Verilator, we see that the number for these unnamed generate blocks don't match the assigned number when there are some named blocks in between.

Relevant part of LRM below. Emphasis mine.

LRM 1800-2012

> 27.6 External names for unnamed generate blocks
>  
> Each generate construct in a given scope is assigned a number. The number will be 1 for the construct that appears textually first in that scope and will increase by 1 for **each subsequent generate construct** in that scope. All unnamed generate blocks will be given the name “genblk<n>” where **<n> is the number assigned to its enclosing generate construct**.


Code sample to demonstrate this issue:
```
// Example to show the genblk naming for signals
module top;
logic [3:0] dataIn = 4'b1010;
// 1
for (genvar i = 0; (i < 8); i++) begin // should be genblk1
    logic [3:0] sig1;
    assign sig1 = dataIn;
end
// 2
for (genvar i = 0; (i < 8); i++) begin // should be genblk2
    logic [3:0] sig2;
    assign sig2 = dataIn;
end
// 3
for (genvar i = 0; (i < 8); i++) begin : Custom3 // should be Custom3
    logic [3:0] sig3;
    assign sig3 = dataIn;
end
// 4
for (genvar i = 0; (i < 8); i++) begin // should be genblk4 and NOT genblk3
    logic [3:0] sig4;
    assign sig4 = dataIn;
end
endmodule // End Top Module
```
In the above example, the generated name for the last block should be genblk4. In Verilator we see it as genblk3.
